Penn State bidding for volleyball Final Four

Michael Grant, mgrant@courier-journal.com 11:07 p.m. EST December 12, 2014

Penn State celebrates after getting a kill against UCLA. The Nittany Lions defeated the Bruins in three straight sets, moving on to play Wisconsin. Dec. 12, 2014(Photo: Scott Utterback/The C-J)

CONNECTTWEETLINKEDINCOMMENTEMAILMORE

Get ready for a clash of the volleyball titans.

No. 5 seed Penn State rolled past No. 12 UCLA 3-0 (28-26, 25-16, 25-19) on Friday in the NCAA tournament's Louisville Regional semifinal, setting up a 4 p.m. Saturday meeting between the Nittany Lions (33-3) and No. 4 Wisconsin (31-2) at the KFC Yum! Center.

This will be a rematch of last year's national championship match won by Penn State. This season, Wisconsin was the Big Ten champion. However, Penn State defeated the Badgers 3-0 in Wisconsin in September. The Nittany Lions are aiming for their seventh NCAA championship.

RELATED: Wisconsin staves off OSU in NCAA volleyball

If Penn State wins Saturday, senior setter Micha Hancock will get to play the Final Four in her home state. She grew up in Edmond — just 14 miles from Oklahoma City, the site of the Final Four.

"This is like a championship match," Hancock said of facing Wisconsin again. "They're a great team. It's going to be an exciting match. We know each other well. It's a game of errors. Whoever makes less errors, wins the game."

    Last year, Penn State coach Russ Rose told his team that the winner of a regional final in Lexington between the Nittany Lions and Stanford would win the national championship. He was right.

    This showdown with Wisconsin may have a similar feeling. The Badgers have won 22 straight matches.

    "(Wisconsin) has so many seniors," Rose said. "They're a confident team. They were able to do what we were not able to do and that was win the Big Ten. When we played them earlier in the year, we played great. They're a great defensive team."

    To get to the regional final, Penn State had to confront a traditional thorn in its side. UCLA had won five of the teams' six NCAA meetings, including 3-0 in 2011 in Lexington, Ky. The first set — 28-26 — was close, but Penn State followed by taking the second 25-16 and third 25-19.

    In the first set, Penn State scored the first four points and held a 9-4 lead. UCLA (22-12) rallied to take an 18-16 lead. With the score tied at 26, Penn State got consecutive kills from Haleigh Washington and Nia Grant to win the set.

    "It wasn't our best match so I'm disappointed that we didn't play our absolute best," UCLA coach Michael Sealy said. "Over the course of the season, we had our ups and downs. Tonight was pretty much a synopsis of what the season was like."

    Penn State's Aiyana Whitney and Washington had 13 and 12 kills respectively.

    "We had a nice gameplan," Rose said. "We did a far better job from the end line than we did in our last match. We're excited about advancing."

    UCLA senior Karsta Lowe had 22 kills, but it wasn't enough against mighty Penn State.

    "They're big and physical," she said. "They move the ball around and they've got some power."
